@REMARK *----------------------------------------------------------*
@REMARK *                    Digits Program                        *
@REMARK *----------------------------------------------------------*
@NODE Digits
@TOC "Instructions/MAIN"
@TITLE "Digits Program"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The @{" Electrics Digits " LINK Picture_Database/Digits.0/MAIN} program behaves like a row of 7-segment
L.E.D. digits, to allow testing a design that would drive such a
display.  Each digit is independent, with decimal-point and colon
elements, including a common-anode or common-cathode selection.

  @{" Window      " LINK Window} - Layout of program window.
  @{" Digit       " LINK Digit} - Digit elements and Signals.
  @{" ARexx       " LINK ARexx} - ARexx support.
  @{" Limitations " LINK Limitations} - Limitations, bugs, etc.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *----------------*
@REMARK *     Window     *
@REMARK *----------------*
@NODE Window
@TOC Digits
@TITLE "Digits Program Window"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Information Box @{fg text}@{bg background}
        
At the top of the @{" program window " LINK Picture_Database/Digits.1/MAIN} lies the Information Box.  This area
is used to indicate program status, and consists of the following 
three lines:

PROJECT: Project name.
TITLE:   Display title.
MESSAGE: Error message or comment.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Digit Box @{fg text}@{bg background}
        
The Digit Box lies just under the Information Box, and contains the
row of digits.  The digit number sequence begins at the right with
zero, and increases to the left.  If the program window is not wide
enough to display all the digits, the left-most ones will not be
visible.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Sheet Box Option @{fg text}@{bg background}

The DARK DIGITBOX option in the SETTINGS menu can be used to change the
colors of the Digit Box.  When the option is "checked", the Digit Box
background color is dark, with a lighter digit element color (LED-look).
Otherwise, the background color is light, with a dark digit element
color (LCD-look).
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-------*
@REMARK * Digit *
@REMARK *-------*
@NODE Digit
@TOC Digits
@TITLE "Elements and Signals"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Elements @{fg text}@{bg background}

Each @{" digit " LINK Picture_Database/Digits.2/MAIN} consists of seven digit segments (labeled "a" through "g"),
with a decimal point and colon to the left.

@{fg background}@{bg text} Signal Drive @{fg text}@{bg background}

Each digit element has a dedicated Signal, including one other Signal
that is common to all the elements.  The state of these Signals
controls the @{" appearance " LINK Picture_Database/Digits.3/MAIN} of the digit elements.

  @{u}COMMON SIGNAL   ELEMENT SIGNAL       RESULT      @{uu}
    Level "0"       Level "0"       Element off
    Level "0"       Level "1"       Element on
    Level "1"       Level "0"       Element on
    Level "1"       Level "1"       Element off
    Level "Z"       Don't Care      Digit off
    Don't Care      Level "Z"       Element off
    Level "X"       Not level "Z"   Element unknown
    Not level "Z"   level "X"       Element unknown
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *----------------------*
@REMARK * Digits ARexx Support *
@REMARK *----------------------*
@NODE ARexx
@TOC Digits
@TITLE "Digits ARexx Support"

@{fg background}@{bg text} Introduction @{fg text}@{bg background}

The Digits program supports an ARexx interface for controlling the
digit elements, and labeling digit Signals.

  @{" Message Port " LINK Port} - ARexx message port.
  @{" Commands     " LINK Commands} - ARexx commands.
  @{" Error Codes  " LINK Errors} - ARexx error codes.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-------------------*
@REMARK * Digits ARexx Port *
@REMARK *-------------------*
@NODE Port
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Digits ARexx Message Port"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Port @{fg text}@{bg background}

Each instance of the Digits program will have a unique ARexx port
name, beginning with the program name, and ending with the instance
number (e.g. DIGITS.1, DIGITS.2, etc.).  The last line of the PROJECT
menu ABOUT requester shows the ARexx port name for the program.
@ENDNODE

@REMARK *-----------------------*
@REMARK * Digits ARexx Commands *
@REMARK *-----------------------*
@NODE Commands
@TOC ARexx
@TITLE "Digits ARexx Commands"

@{fg background}@{bg text} ARexx Commands @{fg text}@{bg background}

DIGITS TOTAL/N

  Sets the total number of digits in the Digit Box.  Although TOTAL
  cannot be higher than 32, the limit will most likely be set by the
  maximum width of the program window.  All old digit Signal names 
  and levels will be cleared when this command is received.

  Example: DIGITS 4

TITLE TEXT/A

  Displays an optional message on the TITLE line in the Information
  Box.  This may be useful to identify the purpose of multiple Digits
  programs running at once.

  Examples: TITLE TIME
            TITLE "NEUTRINO COUNTER"

LABEL DIGIT/N,SIGNAL/A,NAME/A

  Names a digit Signal.  The name must be the same as that of a Signal
  present in the project.  DIGIT is the digit number, and SIGNAL
  selects the digit Signal.  This command must be used before the
  Digits program is connected to the Simulator, since the digit Signal
  names are required at that time.
  
  @{u}SIGNAL     DIGIT CONTROL  @{uu}
  SEGMENTS   Digit segments
  DECIMAL    Decimal point
  COLON      Colon
  COMMON     Common line
  
  All digit segment Signals are named at once, which means that NAME
  is a list of seven names.  The first name in the list is for segment
  "a", the second is for "b", and so on.

  Examples: LABEL 0 COMMON GND
            LABEL 2 SEGMENTS SA SB SC SD SE SF SG

SET DIGIT/N,SIGNAL/A,LEVEL/A

  Manually sets a digit Signal level.  DIGIT is the digit number, and
  SIGNAL selects the digit Signal (See LABEL command).  This command
  is useful for turning off any unused digits or digit elements.
  LEVEL is the Signal level to be set.
  
  @{u}LEVEL   DESCRIPTION @{uu}
    0      Logic Low
    1      Logic High
    X      Unknown
    Z      Floating

  All digit segment Signals are set at once, which means that LEVEL
  is a list of seven levels.  The first level in the list is for
  segment "a", the second is for "b", and so on.
  
  Examples: SET 0 COLON 1
            SET 1 SEGMENTS 1111110

COLOR DARKDIGITBOX/S, LIGHTDIGITBOX/S

  Behaves the same as the DARK DIGITBOX option in the SETTINGS menu.
  The Digit Box colors are changed accordingly. "COLOUR" will also be
  accepted as the command's spelling.

NOP

  This command does nothing.  It could be used for locating a certain
  instance of the Digits program by sending the command to see if it
  is accepted, or if an error occurs instead.
@ENDNODE

